  "doc_id": "110",
  "text": "This work was followed by Haidari and Smith [CITATION_1] who considered finite duration injections through a narrow slot to approximate a turbulent \"burst\" event. They found that not only did secondary hairpin vortices appear upstream of the primary hairpin but that additional hairpins appeared outboard of the primary hairpin legs as a result of the viscous entrainment of surrounding fluid. Following the development downstream, they observed that a single hairpin could develop into a turbulent spot, marking the initiation of transition. Later, DNS calculations by Singer and Joslin 14 corroborated that a single hairpin vortex could produce a young turbulent spot.",
  "correct_citation": {
